{{short description|A chain of seamounts in the Southern Atlantic Ocean}}
{{coord|42|S|0.2|E|display=intitle|notes={{sfn|Jokat|Reents|2017|p=78}}}}
'''Discovery Seamounts''' are a chain of seamounts in the [[Southern Atlantic Ocean]], which include the Discovery Seamount. The seamounts lie {{convert|850|km}} east of [[Gough Island]] and once rose above sea level. Various volcanic rocks as well as glacial [[Dropstone|dropstones]] and sediments have been dredged from the seamounts.

The Discovery Seamounts appear to be a volcanic seamount chain controlled by the '''Discovery hotspot''', which had its starting point either in the ocean, [[Cretaceous]] [[kimberlite]] fields in southern Namibia or the [[Karoo-Ferrar]] [[large igneous province]]. The seamounts formed between 41 and 35 million years ago; presently the hotspot is thought to lie southwest of the seamounts, where there are geological anomalies in the [[Mid-Atlantic Ridge]] that may reflect the presence of a neighbouring hotspot.

== Name and discovery ==

Discovery Seamount was discovered in 1936 by the research ship ''[[RRS Discovery II]]''{{sfn|Kempe|Schilling|1974|p=101}} and was originally named Discovery Bank{{sfn|Buckley|1976|p=937}} by the crew of a German research ship, RV ''Schwabenland''. The seamount received another name, Discovery Tablemount, in 1963. In 1993 the name "Discovery Bank" was transferred by the [[General Bathymetric Chart of the Oceans]] to another seamount at [[Kerguelen]], leaving the name "Discovery Seamounts" for the seamounts.<ref name="SummerhayesLüdecke2012" />

== Geography and geomorphology ==

The Discovery Seamounts are a group of [[seamount]]s{{sfn|Jokat|Reents|2017|p=77}} {{convert|850|km}} east of [[Gough Island]]{{sfn|Kempe|Schilling|1974|p=101}} and southwest from [[Cape Town]]{{sfn|Werner|Hauff|2011|p=6}} which extend over an east-west region of over {{convert|611|km}} length.{{sfn|Buckley|1976|p=937}} The seamounts rise over {{convert|4|km}}{{sfn|Werner|Hauff|2011|p=4}} to depths of {{convert|400|-|500|m}} and have the shape of [[guyot]]s;{{sfn|Schwindrofska|Hoernle|Hauff|van den Bogaard|2016|p=169}} this implies that they formerly rose above sea level,{{sfn|Schwindrofska|Hoernle|Hauff|van den Bogaard|2016|p=170}} guyots form when islands are eroded to a flat plateau that is then submerged through [[thermal subsidence]] of the [[lithosphere]].{{sfn|Werner|Hauff|2011|p=20}} The shallowest peak reached by a seamount from the group is a depth of {{convert|426|m}},<ref name="Richardson2007" /> although a depth of {{convert|389|m}} has been reported for Discovery Seamount also.<ref name="Pushcharovskii2004" /> These seamounts are also referred to as the Discovery Rise and subdivided into a northwestern and a southeastern trend.{{sfn|Schwindrofska|Hoernle|Hauff|van den Bogaard|2016|p=168}} 

The largest of these seamounts is named Discovery Seamount,{{sfn|Jokat|Reents|2017|p=78}} which given its shape might once have been an island.{{sfn|Kempe|Schilling|1974|p=102}} The seamount is covered with [[fossil]]-containing sediments,{{sfn|Buckley|1976|p=937}} which have been used to infer [[paleoclimate]] conditions in the region during the [[Pleistocene]].{{sfn|Buckley|1976|pp=943-944}} Some of the sediment appears to be [[ice-rafted debris]],{{sfn|Buckley|1976|p=945}} and other evidence has been used to postulate that the seamount subsided by about {{convert|0.5|km}} during the late [[Pleistocene]].{{sfn|Buckley|1976|p=947}} Another member of the Discovery Seamounts has been christened Shannon Seamount.{{sfn|le Roex|Class|O'Connor|Jokat|2010|p=2091}}

The [[crust (geology)|crust]] underneath Discovery Seamount is about 67 million years old, thus of late [[Cretaceous]] age.{{sfn|Kempe|Schilling|1974|p=102}} A [[fracture zone]], thus a site of [[crust (geology)|crust]]al weakness, is located nearby.{{sfn|Jokat|Reents|2017|p=84}} 

== Geology ==

The [[Southern Atlantic Ocean]] contains a number of volcanic systems such as the Discovery Seamounts, the [[Rio Grande Rise]], the [[Shona Ridge]] and the [[Walvis Ridge]] which are commonly attributed to [[hotspot (geology)|hotspot]]s,{{sfn|Jokat|Reents|2017|p=77}} although this interpretation has been challenged.{{sfn|Jokat|Reents|2017|p=78}} The hotspot origin of Discovery and the Walvis-[[Tristan da Cunha]] seamount chains was first proposed in 1972.{{sfn|Kempe|Schilling|1974|p=101}} In the case of the Shona Ridge and the Discovery Seamounts, the theory postulates that they formed as the [[African Plate]] moved over the [[Shona hotspot]] and the Discovery hotspot.{{sfn|le Roex|Class|O'Connor|Jokat|2010|p=2090}}

It is not clear if a Discovery Hotspot exists, nor whether it is linked in any way to Gough Island.{{sfn|Jokat|Reents|2017|p=78}} The formation of the Discovery Seamounts may instead have been caused by ascent of [[magma]] along a fracture zone or other crustal weakness.{{sfn|Jokat|Reents|2017|p=89}} If the hotspot does exist, it would have to be located southwest of the Discovery Seamounts{{sfn|Schwindrofska|Hoernle|Hauff|van den Bogaard|2016|p=168}} where low seismic velocity anomalies have been detected in the [[mantle (geology)|mantle]].{{sfn|Homrighausen|Hoernle|Hauff|Wartho|2018|p=6}} The Discovery Seamounts almost wane out in that direction although the it has been proposed that the Little Ridge close to the Mid-Atlantic Ridge may be their continuation.{{sfn|Schwindrofska|Hoernle|Hauff|van den Bogaard|2016|p=171}} The Discovery Ridge close to the Mid-Atlantic Ridge{{sfn|Gibson|Richards|2018|p=209}} may be the product of the hotspot as well; magma flowing from the Discovery hotspot to the Mid-Atlantic Ridge{{sfn|Gibson|Richards|2018|p=205}} may be leading to excessive production of [[Crust (geology)|crust]]al material there.{{sfn|Gibson|Richards|2018|p=216}}

Petrological anomalies at [[spreading ridge]]s have been often attributed to the presence of [[mantle plume]]s close to the ridge and such has been proposed for the Discovery hotspot as well.{{sfn|Douglass|Schilling|Kingsley|Small|1995|p=2893}} There is a region on the [[Mid-Atlantic Ridge]] southwest of the seamounts where there are fewer [[earthquake]]s than elsewhere along the ridge, the central valley of the ridge is absent<ref name="DeAlteriis1998" /> and where dredged rocks share geochemical traits with the Discovery Seamount; that may be the location of the Discovery Hotspot.{{sfn|Schwindrofska|Hoernle|Hauff|van den Bogaard|2016|p=168}} A position about halfway between the Mid-Atlantic Ridge and the Discovery Seamounts has been inferred.{{sfn|Douglass|Schilling|Kingsley|Small|1995|p=2894}} The Discovery hotspot may be connected to the [[Tristan hotspot]] deep in the mantle.{{sfn|Homrighausen|Hoernle|Hauff|Wartho|2018|p=25}}

The South Atlantic features one of the largest [[transform fault]]s of Earth, the Agulhas-Falkland fracture zone.{{sfn|Uenzelmann-Neben|Gohl|2004|p=305}} This transform fault has an unusual structure on the [[African Plate]], where it displays the [[Agulhas Ridge]], two over {{convert|2|km}} high ridge segments which are parallel to each other.{{sfn|Uenzelmann-Neben|Gohl|2004|p=306}} This unusual structure may be due to magma from the Discovery hotspot, which would have been channelled to the Agulhas Ridge.{{sfn|Uenzelmann-Neben|Gohl|2004|p=316}}

=== Composition ===

Rocks dredged from the seamounts include [[lava]]s, [[pillow lava]]s and [[volcaniclastic]] rocks.{{sfn|Werner|Hauff|2011|p=11}} Geochemically they are classified as [[alkali basalt]], [[basalt]], [[phonolite]], [[tephriphonolite]]{{sfn|Schwindrofska|Hoernle|Hauff|van den Bogaard|2016|p=169}} [[trachyandesite]], [[trachybasalt]] and [[trachyte]].{{sfn|le Roex|Class|O'Connor|Jokat|2010|p=2094}} Minerals contained in the rocks include [[alkali feldspar]], [[apatite]], [[biotite]], [[clinopyroxene]], iron and titanium oxides, [[olivine]], [[plagioclase]], [[sphene]] and [[spinel]].{{sfn|Schwindrofska|Hoernle|Hauff|van den Bogaard|2016|p=169}} Continental crust rocks dredged at the seamounts may be glacial [[dropstone]]s,{{sfn|le Roex|Class|O'Connor|Jokat|2010|p=2093}} [[manganese]] have also been found.{{sfn|Werner|Hauff|2011|p=11}}

The Discovery hotspot appears to have erupted two separate sets of [[magma]]s with distinct compositions, similar to the [[Tristan da Cunha]]-[[Gough Island]] hotspot.{{sfn|Schwindrofska|Hoernle|Hauff|van den Bogaard|2016|p=175}} The composition of the Discovery Seamounts rocks has been compared to [[Gough Island]].{{sfn|Jokat|Reents|2017|p=77}} The more [[felsic]] rocks at Discovery appear to be derived from [[magma chamber]] processes, similar to felsic rocks at other Atlantic Ocean islands.{{sfn|le Roex|Class|O'Connor|Jokat|2010|p=2109}}

== Biology ==

[[Soviet Union|Soviet]] fishery during the 1970s and 1980s and others have found {{circa}} 150 fish species at Discovery Seamount.<ref name="BalushkinPrirodina2010" /> Both Japanese and Soviet trawled the seamounts during that time, but there was no commercial exploitation of the resources.<ref name="SeamountsEcology2007" /> The [[Morids|codling]] ''[[Guttigadus nudirostre]]'' is [[endemic]] to Discovery Seamount.<ref name="Melendez1997" /> Fossil [[coral]]s have been recovered in dredges.{{sfn|Werner|Hauff|2011|p=24}}

== Eruption history ==

A number of dates ranging from 41 to 35 million years ago have been obtained on dredged samples from the seamounts on the basis of [[argon-argon dating]],{{sfn|Schwindrofska|Hoernle|Hauff|van den Bogaard|2016|p=168}} but at Discovery Seamount it may have continued until 7-6.5 million years ago.{{sfn|Buckley|1976|p=947}} The age of the seamounts decreases in southwest direction, similar to the Walvis Ridge, and at a similar rate.{{sfn|Schwindrofska|Hoernle|Hauff|van den Bogaard|2016|p=170}} 

Unlike the Walvis Ridge, which is connected to the [[Etendeka]] [[flood basalt]]s, the Discovery Seamounts do not link with onshore volcanic features.{{sfn|Jokat|Reents|2017|p=77}} However, it has been proposed that the 70-80 million years old Blue Hills, Gibeon and Gross Brukkaros [[kimberlite]] fields in southern [[Namibia]] may have been formed by the Discovery hotspot,<ref name="ReidCooper2009" /> and some plate reconstructions place it underneath the [[Karoo-Ferrar]] [[large igneous province]] at the time at which it was emplaced.<ref name="StoreyLeat2001" />

