{{Infobox book | name = Path of the Puma | image = Cover_path_of_the_puma.jpg | author = Jim Williams | language = English | country = U.S.A. | genre = Non-fiction | published = 2018 | publisher = Patagonia Books | isbn = 978-1-938340-72-7 }}
'''''Path of the Puma: The Remarkable Resilience of the Mountain Lion''''', by Jim Williams, is a non-fiction book presenting the research of the author, a [[wildlife biologist]] and supervisor for Montana Fish, Wildlife and Parks' Region 1 in [[Kalispell, Montana|Kalispell]]. Williams also discusses [[DNA]] research conducted by others on these animals, and makes the case for coexistence with these big, wild cats
== Synopsis == [[File:Jim WIlliams author photo.jpg|thumb|left|Author Jim Williams]] With a foreword by [[Douglas H. Chadwick|Doug Chadwick]], the book chronicles Williams' journey, from his early work at a Florida marine park, to his conversion to "a lifelong devotee of the species".<ref name=":0" /> Williams has fitted [[Puma (genus)|pumas]] (also known as cougars and mountain lions) with [[Tracking collar|radio collars]] and has installed cameras in their caves to track and study them.<ref name=":0">{{Cite news|url=https://www.publishersweekly.com/pw/reviews/single/9781938340727|title=Nonfiction Book Review: Path of the Puma: The Remarkable Resilience of the Mountain Lion|last=|first=|date=6 August 2018|work=Publishers Weekly|access-date=2 September 2018|language=en}}</ref><ref name=":1">{{Cite journal|last=|first=|date=1 September 2018|title=Path of the Puma: the Remarkable Resilience of the Mountain Lion|url=https://www.kirkusreviews.com/book-reviews/jim-williams/path-of-the-puma/|journal=Kirkus Reviews|volume=|pages=|isbn=978-1-938340-72-7|via=}}</ref> [[Publishers Weekly|''Publishers Weekly'']] wrote, "Montana-based wildlife biologist Jim Williams celebrates wildlife research and conservation of ghost cats from Canada’s [[Yukon|Yukon Territory]] to [[Tierra del Fuego]] in Argentina and Chile..."<ref name=":0" />
== Critical reception ==
''Path of the Puma'' has received positive reviews. ''Publishers Weekly'' said, "Williams writes movingly of the challenges these animals face, many due to human encroachment on their habitats. He makes a strong case for the necessity of preserving—or at least peacefully coexisting with—the puma."<ref name=":0" /> [[Kirkus Reviews|''Kirkus Reviews'']] noted, "While the book is an undisguised conservationist’s plea ... it is not a harangue. The author’s passion and his firsthand knowledge of his subject make the narrative highly readable. A noteworthy feature of this work is the presence of numerous full-color photographs..."<ref name=":1" /> Kirkus concluded, "A handsome book that is well-balanced, instructive, and authoritative."<ref name=":1" /> The Natural History Book Service wrote that the puma's story, "...is fascinating for the lessons it can afford the protection of all species in times of dire challenge and decline."<ref name=":2">{{Cite web|url=https://www.nhbs.com/path-of-the-puma-book|title=Path of the Puma: The Remarkable Resilience of the Mountain Lion|website=www.nhbs.com|language=en-US|access-date=2018-09-02}}</ref>
Susan Waggoner of [[PressReader]] notes Williams' "...enthusiasm for nature and animals jumps off every page... Williams’s writing is expert, friendly, and interesting. Well organized and clearly presented, information emerges from field work examples, such as the tracking studies that showed that pumas feed almost exclusively on wild prey rather than domestic herds."<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pressreader.com/usa/foreword-reviews/20180814/282746292607191|title=Path of the Puma|last=Waggoner|first=Susan|date=14 August 2018|website=www.pressreader.com|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=2018-09-02}}</ref> Tristan Scott of the Flathead Beacon wrote, "''Path of the Puma'' doesn’t sugarcoat the risks of predators living among humans — mountain lions live at the intersection of human landscapes, livelihoods and lifestyles — but it points out the critical role predatory species play in the natural world."<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://flatheadbeacon.com/2018/08/31/pursuing-the-puma/|title=Pursuing the Puma - Flathead Beacon|last=Scott|first=Tristan|date=31 August 2018|work=Flathead Beacon|access-date=2018-09-02|language=en-US}}</ref>
